<p class=MsoNormal><b><span lang=EN-US>&nbsp;</span></b></p>
<h2><span lang=EN-US>Presenting symptoms and signs </span></h2>
<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>These become obvious as the hypernatraemia
becomes more severe:</span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Thirst</span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Fever </span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Sensorium change</span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Seizure </span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Focal neurological deficits</span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpLast style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Hyperventilation</span></p>
<span lang=EN-US style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'><br
clear=all style='page-break-before:always'>
</span>
<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:0cm;margin-bottom:.0001pt'><b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:12.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></b></p>
<h2><span lang=EN-US>Management</span></h2>
<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>Stop or decrease dosage of medications and
infusions which are likely causes of hypernatremia.</span></p>
<h3><span lang=EN-US>Adults</span></h3>
<p class=MsoNormal><b><span lang=EN-US>Mild to moderate hypernatraemia</span></b><span
lang=EN-US> (Na 146-159 mmol/l): oral water therapy may be sufficient. </span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><b><span lang=EN-US>Severe hypernatraemia</span></b><span
lang=EN-US> (Na &gt; 160 mmol/l): use IV 5% Dextrose with the aim to reduce Na
at a rate of 0.5 mmol/hr and not more than 10 mmol/24hrs. Monitor Na every 4
hours. Note that too rapid a correction of the Na can cause cerebral oedema,
convulsions and brain injury. </span></p>
<h3><span lang=EN-US>Children</span></h3>
<p class=MsoNormal><b><span lang=EN-US>Mild hypernatraemia </span></b><span
lang=EN-US>(Na 146-149 mmol/l): enourage drinking. Stop any feed fortifications
(eg extra scoops of formula – not F75 or F100).</span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><b><span lang=EN-US>Moderate hypernatraemia </span></b><span
lang=EN-US>(Na 150-169 mmol/l):</span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:3.75pt;background:white'><span
lang=EN-US>If &quot;shocked&quot;, resuscitate with boluses 20ml/kg of 0.9%
saline as required.</span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>After initial resuscitation, replace the
deficit plus maintenance slowly at a uniform rate </span><span lang=EN-US><a
href="https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Hypernatraemia/#1"
title="over 48 hours"><span style='color:windowtext'>over 48 hours</span></a></span><b><span
lang=EN-US>.</span></b><span lang=EN-US> </span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Nasogastric rehydration is preferred</span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Courier New"'>o<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Carefully regulate fluid intake - do not allow
excessive intake in a thirsty child.</span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Courier New"'>o<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>If the serum sodium falls too rapidly (&gt; 0.5
mmol/l/hr) slow the rate of rehydration (for example, by 20%) or change to
intravenous fluids. </span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>If needing intravenous rehydration use <b>0.9%
sodium chloride (normal saline) and 5% Glucose</b>. Add maintenance KCl once urine
output established. </span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Check U&amp;Es and glucose frequently intially. </span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>If after 6 hours of rehydration therapy, the
sodium is decreasing at a steady rate then check the U&amp;Es and glucose 4
hourly.</span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpLast style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>If serum sodium is falling faster than 1 mmol/l/hr,
stop infusate and seek senior support.</span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><b><span lang=EN-US>Severe hypernatraemia </span></b><span
lang=EN-US>(Na &gt; 170 mmol/l):</span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>This is a medical emergency. </span><span
lang=EN-US>After initial resuscitation, aim to replace deficit and maintenance
with<b> 0.9% sodium chloride (normal saline) and 5% glucose</b> over 72 - 96
hours. Seek senior support early and monitor U&amp;Es up to hourly. Involve lab
staff as soon as possible.</span></p>
<h3><span lang=EN-US>Calculation</span></h3>
<p class=MsoListParagraph style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Water deficit (in litres) = TBW × ([Na/140] – 1 </span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>This determines the amount of fluid to be
infused over 48 hours. </span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraph style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Change in Na = Infusate Na – Na / (total body
water +1) </span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>This gives the change in Na per litre of
infusate. If using 5% dextrose the infusate Na is 0.</span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>You may use the calculator on this website
to determine the rate of fluid infusion : <a
href="https://www.mdcalc.com/sodium-correction-rate-hyponatremia-hypernatremia">https://www.mdcalc.com/sodium-correction-rate-hyponatremia-hypernatremia</a>
</span></p>
<h2><span lang=EN-US>Key Issues for Nursing care</span></h2>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Severe hyponatraemia and hypernatraemia can both
have serious long term consequences. These can be worsened if the correction is
too rapid.</span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Follow the fluid instructions very carefully. </span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>Make sure repeat tests are done on time and are
reviewed by a doctor promptly. </span></p>
<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpLast style='text-indent:-18.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US>All patients with abnormal Na levels should have
strict monitoring of fluid input and output.</span></p>
